---
import TutorialLayout from '../../layouts/TutorialLayout.astro';

const recommendedGear = [
  { title: "Best Kitchen Scale", href: "/reviews/kitchen/best-kitchen-scale/", description: "Track your portions with precision." },
  { title: "Best Air Fryer", href: "/reviews/kitchen/best-air-fryer/", description: "Cook hot dogs with less added fat." }
];
---

<TutorialLayout
  title="Costco Hot Dog Calories Without Bun — Complete Breakdown"
  description="Detailed calorie and macro breakdown of Costco hot dogs without the bun. Perfect for keto, low-carb, and calorie-conscious eaters."
  recommendedGear={recommendedGear}
>
  <p>
    If you're watching your carbs, following a ketogenic diet, or simply trying to reduce your calorie intake, eating a Costco hot dog without the bun is a smart choice. Here's the complete nutritional breakdown.
  </p>

  <h2>Calories Without Bun</h2>
  <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <div class="text-center">
      <span class="text-5xl font-bold text-green-700">370</span>
      <p class="text-lg text-green-600 mt-2">calories per hot dog (without bun)</p>
    </div>
    <p class="text-center text-gray-600 mt-4">
      That's <strong>200 fewer calories</strong> than with the bun (570 total).
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Complete Macro Breakdown (No Bun)</h2>
  <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse mt-4 mb-6">
    <thead>
      <tr class="bg-gray-100">
        <th class="p-3 border">Nutrient</th>
        <th class="p-3 border">Amount</th>
        <th class="p-3 border">% of Daily Value*</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="p-3 border font-semibold">Calories</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">370</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">18.5%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="bg-gray-50">
        <td class="p-3 border font-semibold">Total Fat</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">33g</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">42%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="p-3 border pl-6">Saturated Fat</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">13g</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">65%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="bg-gray-50">
        <td class="p-3 border font-semibold">Cholesterol</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">75mg</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">25%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="p-3 border font-semibold">Sodium</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">1,050mg</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">46%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="bg-gray-50">
        <td class="p-3 border font-semibold">Total Carbs</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">3g</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">1%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="p-3 border pl-6">Dietary Fiber</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">0g</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">0%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="bg-gray-50">
        <td class="p-3 border pl-6">Sugars</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">2g</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">—</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="p-3 border font-semibold text-green-700">Protein</td>
        <td class="p-3 border font-semibold">24g</td>
        <td class="p-3 border">48%</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">*Based on a 2,000 calorie diet.</p>

  <h2>Keto and Low-Carb Friendly</h2>
  <p>
    At only 3g of carbohydrates, a Costco hot dog without the bun fits easily into most low-carb and ketogenic diets. Here's how it compares to other popular keto proteins:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Costco hot dog (no bun):</strong> 3g carbs, 24g protein, 33g fat</li>
    <li><strong>Grilled chicken breast (4oz):</strong> 0g carbs, 35g protein, 4g fat</li>
    <li><strong>Beef patty (80/20, 4oz):</strong> 0g carbs, 20g protein, 23g fat</li>
    <li><strong>Pork sausage (2 links):</strong> 1g carbs, 12g protein, 24g fat</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The high fat content of the hot dog makes it particularly suitable for keto dieters who need to maintain a high fat intake.
  </p>

  <h2>Low-Sodium Modifications</h2>
  <p>
    At 1,050mg of sodium, the hot dog alone accounts for nearly half your daily recommended sodium intake. If you're monitoring sodium:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Drink plenty of water to help flush excess sodium</li>
    <li>Balance with low-sodium meals for the rest of the day</li>
    <li>Consider the <a href="/nutrition/weight-watchers-points/" class="text-green-700 hover:underline">WW Points</a> if you're on Weight Watchers</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Bottom Line</h2>
  <p>
    Ditching the bun turns the Costco hot dog from a moderate-calorie treat (570 cal) into a protein-packed, low-carb meal (370 cal, 3g carbs). It's an excellent choice for keto dieters, those managing blood sugar, or anyone looking to reduce calorie intake while still enjoying this iconic food.
  </p>
</TutorialLayout>
